data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0) →
    CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(users);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)) →
    CollectionAssert.That.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3) →
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null) →
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Why these are better:**

| `Assert.IsTrue(...)` | Better alternative | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `users.Count > 0` | `CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty()` | Failure says "collection was empty" vs. "expected true, got false" |
| `users.All(predicate)` | `CollectionAssert.That.AllSatisfy()` | Reports *which* item failed |
| `count == 3` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | Shows "expected 3, got 2" |
| `admin != null` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Clearer intent and message |

> **Note:** `CollectionAssert.That` requires **MSTest v3.8+**. On older versions, `Assert.AreEqual` / `Assert.IsNotNull` still apply, but `AllSatisfy` and `IsNotEmpty` aren't available — you'd stick with `Assert.IsTrue` + LINQ or iterate manually.
